CHAPTER LIII.

17 ς 1,. degeneratum ln aliis] ‘his degeneracy in other respects.’ This use of the perf. part. by itself to denote a state of things is very rare. It seems to have been developed from such impersonal phrases as nuntiatum est, auditum est, treated participially, and so substantivally (e.g. xxvu. 37. 5 liberatas religione mentes turbavit rursus nuntiatum). A few other instances occur in Livy (e. g. vn. 8. 5 diu non perlitatum tenuerat dictatorem), and there is one well known in Virgil, Aen. v. 7 notumque florens quid femina possit. The Greek formatioris in which the neuter article with perf. part. or perf. infin. passive produces a substantive may have suggested the construction in Latin.
